HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1253
By Behn
A RESOLUTION to honor Transgender Day of Visibility and the
resilience, contributions, and dignity of the
transgender community in Tennessee.
WHEREAS, March 31st is the International Transgender Day of Visibility—a day to honor
the achievements, contributions, and enduring resilience of transgender and gender-diverse
people everywhere; and
WHEREAS, Transgender Day of Visibility calls on each of us to see, affirm, and stand
alongside our transgender neighbors—not just on this day, but every day—and to reckon
honestly with the discrimination and harm they continue to face; and
WHEREAS, Tennessee is home to more than 56,100 transgender adults—our
neighbors, coworkers, family members, and fellow Tennesseans—who deserve the full
protection and dignity that every resident of this State is owed; and
WHEREAS, the Human Rights Campaign has found that since 2015, Tennessee has
enacted more anti-LGBTQ+ laws than any other state in the country, including bans on gender-
affirming medical care, bathroom restrictions, and targeted rollbacks of basic civil protections—
making Tennessee increasingly hostile to transgender people who simply want to live their lives;
and
WHEREAS, thirty anti-trans bills were tracked in Tennessee in 2025 alone, and in 2026,
this legislature is advancing bills that would allow private citizens to refuse to recognize same-
sex marriages, ban Pride flags on government property, and —most alarmingly—create a
publicly accessible database of transgender residents, a measure civil rights advocates have
compared to state-sanctioned surveillance and a government catalog of identity itself; and
WHEREAS, according to the Human Rights Campaign Foundation's 2025 Annual
Survey, 43.9 percent of transgender and gender-expansive adults reported experiencing
HJR1253
016936
- 1 -

discrimination based on their gender identity or expression; 57.6 percent said they are less open
about their LGBTQ+ identities than a year ago; and 58.5 percent said they are less visible in
daily life—a chilling reminder that fear, not freedom, is shaping the daily reality of transgender
Tennesseans; and
WHEREAS, the Human Rights Campaign documented at least thirty-two transgender
and gender-expansive people were killed in the United States in 2024, and 56 percent of those
killed were Black transgender women—a devastating and disproportionate toll that demands our
attention and our action; and
WHEREAS, Advocates for Trans Equality documented twenty-seven additional deaths
by violence in the year leading up to Trans Day of Remembrance 2025, with fifty-eight total
known transgender deaths in that period, including those lost to suicide—lives cut short by a
climate of hostility that this legislature has too often fueled rather than fought; and
WHEREAS, transgender people have always existed, have always resisted, and have
always refused to be erased—their history is American history, woven into the fabric of every
fight this country has ever waged for freedom and equal dignity; and
WHEREAS, on June 28, 1969, Marsha P. Johnson and Sylvia Rivera were on the front
lines at the Stonewall Inn when patrons fought back against a police raid—two transgender
women of color, marginalized and unhoused, who risked everything because they, like all
people, believed they deserved to live freely; and
WHEREAS, in 1970, Sylvia Rivera and Marsha Johnson founded the Street Transvestite
Action Revolutionaries (STAR) and created STAR House on East 2nd Street—the first shelter of
its kind in the nation—to provide family support structures for trans youth of color because they
knew that survival required both resistance and community care; and
WHEREAS, the transgender community has faced systematic erasure before—pushed
to the margins of the very liberation movements they helped build, told their existence was too
- 2 - 016936

controversial, too disruptive, too much—and they kept fighting anyway because that is what it
means to be part of a community that has never had the luxury of giving up; and
WHEREAS, today, as the federal government removes transgender people from
national monuments, strips protections that have stood for decades, and attempts to legislate
transgender identity out of existence, transgender Americans are once again showing the rest of
us what resistance looks like—testifying at committee hearings, organizing in their communities,
filing lawsuits, running for office, and simply living openly in defiance of a political moment that
tells them not to; and
WHEREAS, more than half of transgender adults surveyed say they are less open about
their identities than they were a year ago—and yet they are still here, still showing up, still
building lives of meaning and joy in communities that too often fail to protect them; and
WHEREAS, history has never been kind to those who tried to legislate people out of
existence, and history has always vindicated those who refused to disappear; and
WHEREAS, history was made right here in Nashville when Dr. Marisa Richmond—
retired professor, author, and tireless advocate—became the first transgender person elected to
the Democratic National Committee; Dr. Richmond has also served on the Nashville Mayor's
Council on the Status of Women and the Davidson County General Sessions Court Judicial
Equity Collective; and
WHEREAS, Olivia Hill made history as the first transgender person elected to the
Nashville Metro Council, proving that representation is possible even in the face of opposition;
and
WHEREAS, Chaplain Dahron Johnson broke a barrier for all Tennesseans by becoming
the first transgender person to lead the opening prayer on the floor of this State house; and
- 3 - 016936

WHEREAS, across every county in this State, transgender Tennesseans are teachers,
nurses, farmers, parents, and public servants—people who get up every day and give to their
communities, even as their government too often fails them; and
WHEREAS, this General Assembly has an obligation to acknowledge both the courage it
takes to live openly as a transgender person in Tennessee today and the responsibility we bear
to do better by every Tennessean regardless of who they are; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we hereby honor Transgender Day of Visibility and the dignity, resilience,
and full humanity of transgender Tennesseans.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
